  "body": "# Description\r\n\r\nSome time ago we were discussing how to map Figma designs to components/views in code. I did some research and pocs to figure out how it could be automated and potentially integrated with storybook. I noticed two imo interesting things:\r\n\r\n1. Figma designs can be easily accessed from qml via their API and therefore it can be quite easily searchable (first video). It's presented for only Kuba-design but it could easily cover all designs (only Kuba - over 3K top level items (!), the full file is over 100MB). It's usable even in current shape but it heavily depends on quality of the titles used in Figma - some titles are not descriptive enough.\r\n2. For given Figma link it's easy to construct query for PNG representation of the pointed item (second video). It creates nice opportunity of adding those links to storybook model. When opening storybook page we could have all the designs listed in model related to the opened page nicely presented (e.g. in a separate tab).\r\n\r\nBoth points can be integrated with storybook relatively easily. The first one could be standalone app as well if needed. Additionally it would enforce putting more attention to naming of the stuff in figma to have the search more effective in the future.\r\n\r\n[Kazam_screencast_00075.webm](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20650004/198027913-bc2a00ce-318b-4d76-b615-70aaba66309c.webm)\r\n\r\n[Kazam_screencast_00076.webm](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20650004/198028036-43ce7e2f-436c-4178-9e83-9186c3d399a3.webm)\r\n",
